    "MS Islamic Studies": {
      "description": "The Department offers an MS in Islamic Studies, a broad-based program that focuses on contemporary socio-political and economic issues, Ijtihad, the objectives of Islamic Shariah, Islamic philosophy, international relations, the Islamic worldview, and the contemporary study of major world religions. Researchers are encouraged to work on practical issues to meet the needs of society and humanity. The MS degree is awarded after the completion of 30 credit hours, with 24 credit hours of coursework and an additional 6 credit hours which can be fulfilled either through a research thesis or by taking two additional courses."
    },
    "PhD Islamic Studies": {
      "description": "The Doctor of Philosophy (Ph.D.) in Islamic Studies is the highest degree awarded by the Department. The program comprises 18 credit hours of coursework and 30 credit hours of research thesis. Courses are selected in consultation with the thesis supervisor, and student progress is continuously monitored by the Guidance and Evaluation Committee (GEC). Eligible candidates must possess an MS/M.Phil. degree with a minimum CGPA of 3.0 out of 4 and have passed the GAT subject examination as per HEC requirements. Coursework completion is followed by a comprehensive examination for Ph.D. candidacy. The program requires two years of residency at HITEC University and involves an open thesis defense after evaluation by one local and two foreign experts. The degree is awarded in recognition of high-level scholarship, independent research ability, and publication of research in reputed journals. The Department encourages research on current and futuristic issues related to the renaissance of Islamic thought, philosophy, and scientific knowledge."
    }
  },
